@startuml fig-line-coding-overview
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam roundcorner 12

title Line Coding Schemes: NRZ, NRZI and Manchester

rectangle "Bit Sequence: 1 0 1 1 0 0 1 0" as bits #FFF9C4

rectangle "NRZ (Non-Return-to-Zero)\nHigh = 1, Low = 0\nNo transition within bit period\nProblem: long runs lose sync" as nrz #BBDEFB

rectangle "NRZI (NRZ Inverted)\nTransition at start = 1\nNo transition = 0\nBetter for runs of 1s" as nrzi #BBDEFB

rectangle "Manchester\nMid-bit transition encodes data\nHigh-to-low = 1, Low-to-high = 0\nSelf-clocking, but doubles bandwidth" as man #BBDEFB

bits -down-> nrz : encode
bits -down-> nrzi : encode
bits -down-> man : encode

legend bottom
  Line coding maps bits to voltage levels on copper.
  The goal is to maintain clock synchronisation
  and avoid prolonged DC components.
  Manchester guarantees a transition every bit period.
endlegend
@enduml
